  "text": "Third-place play-off · 18 July 2026. Final score: France 4–6 England. A ten-goal bronze-medal classic ended with England on top — and a scoring record for Kylian Mbappé.\n\nOfficially a match for third place; unofficially, one of the maddest games the tournament produced.\n\nThe goals, in sequence: 3′ Declan Rice — 0–1; 18′ Ezri Konsa — 0–2; 38′ Bukayo Saka — 0–3; 46′ Bukayo Saka — 0–4; 48′ Kylian Mbappé — 1–4; 54′ Bradley Barcola — 2–4; 66′ Kylian Mbappé — 3–4; 87′ Bukayo Saka (pen) — 3–5; 96′ Ousmane Dembélé — 4–5; 98′ Jude Bellingham — 4–6. That is 10 goals in all, France accounting for 4 and England 6.\n\nEngland raced into a four-goal lead through Declan Rice, Ezri Konsa and a Bukayo Saka double, and it looked like a rout. France roared back: Kylian Mbappé struck twice around a Bradley Barcola goal to close it to 3-4 and set nerves jangling. But Saka completed his hat-trick from the penalty spot, Ousmane Dembélé kept France alive, and Jude Bellingham had the very last word. Mbappé's double moved him above Lionel Messi as the World Cup's all-time leading scorer — yet it was England who went home with the bronze.\n\nFor the record, England advanced. Goal, team and minute for every event above are Merkle-proven on Solana devnet via TxLINE; the scorer names are attributed from public match reports and aligned to the verified goals by team and order. Nothing here rests on the commentator's word alone.",
